Nasarawa State House of Assembly has taken steps to address substance abuse among youths in the state. To this end, the Assembly has organised a public hearing on a bill for a law to prohibit substance abuse and to provide treatment for substance abusers and addicts in 2021. The Chairman of the House Committee on Health, Usman Labaran Shafa, said the public hearing was organised in order to get inputs from the stakeholders on the bill. He said the bill if passed into law, was aimed to prohibit substance abuse and provide treatment for substance abusers.   Protest in Abuja over persistent kidnapping     25 inmates among 22, 250 to receive NOUN degrees     2023: 45 Northern CSOs clamour for Igbo president   Shafa, who represents Toto/ Gadabuke State Constituency at the House of Assembly, said substance abuse has affected the lives of many youths and other Nigerians negatively, hence the need for all hands to be on deck to tackle it. Also, Dr Ikrama Hassan, Chief Medical Director (CMD) Dalhatu Araf Specialist Hospital (DASH) , Lafia described the bill as excellent and timely. He commended the sponsor of the bill for the initiative which he said will go a long way in addressing a lot of societal problems. Other health experts and stakeholders, who spoke during the public hearing called for the establishment of a rehabilitation and skill acquisition centre for drug abusers and addicts. They have also called for more awareness campaigns against substance abuse in order to discourage people from drug abuse, especially the dealers and end-users for the overall development of the country.